# Control Structures in Java

## Introduction

Control structures are statements used to control the flow of execution of a Java program.

They decide:
- Which statement should execute
- How many times a statement should execute
- In what order statements should execute


# Types of Control Structures in Java

Java provides three main types of control structures:

1. Decision Making Statements
2. Looping Statements
3. Jump Statements


# 1. Decision Making Statements

Decision making statements execute a block of code based on a condition.

Types:

- if statement
- if-else statement
- else-if ladder
- nested if
- switch statement


## if Statement

The if statement executes code only when the condition is true.


Syntax:

if(condition)
{
    // statements
}


Example:

```java
int age = 20;

if(age >= 18)
{
    System.out.println("Eligible");
}

if-else Statement

The if-else statement executes one block when condition is true and another block when condition is false.

Syntax:

if(condition)
{
// true block
}
else
{
// false block
}

Example:

int num = 5;

if(num % 2 == 0)
{
    System.out.println("Even");
}
else
{
    System.out.println("Odd");
}
else-if Ladder

Used when we have multiple conditions.

Syntax:

if(condition1)
{

}
else if(condition2)
{

}
else
{

}

Example:

int marks = 80;

if(marks >= 90)
{
    System.out.println("A Grade");
}
else if(marks >= 60)
{
    System.out.println("B Grade");
}
else
{
    System.out.println("C Grade");
}
Nested if

An if statement inside another if statement is called nested if.

Example:

int age = 20;

if(age >= 18)
{
    if(age <= 60)
    {
        System.out.println("Allowed");
    }
}
Switch Statement

Switch is used to execute one block from multiple choices.

Syntax:

switch(expression)
{
case value:
statements;
break;

default:
statements;
}

Example:

int day = 2;

switch(day)
{
case 1:
    System.out.println("Monday");
    break;

case 2:
    System.out.println("Tuesday");
    break;

default:
    System.out.println("Invalid");
}
2. Looping Statements

Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly.

Types:

for loop
while loop
do-while loop
for Loop

Used when the number of iterations is known.

Syntax:

for(initialization; condition; increment)
{

}

Example:

for(int i=1; i<=5; i++)
{
    System.out.println(i);
}
while Loop

Executes statements while the condition is true.

Syntax:

while(condition)
{

}

Example:

int i = 1;

while(i <= 5)
{
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
do-while Loop

Executes the block at least once before checking the condition.

Syntax:

do
{

}
while(condition);

Example:

int i = 1;

do
{
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
while(i<=5);
Difference between while and do-while

while:

Condition is checked first
May execute zero times

do-while:

Executes first then checks condition
Executes at least once
3. Jump Statements

Jump statements transfer control from one place to another.

Types:

break
continue
return
break Statement

Used to terminate a loop immediately.

Example:

for(int i=1;i<=5;i++)
{
    if(i==3)
    {
        break;
    }

    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1
2

continue Statement

Skips the current iteration and moves to the next iteration.

Example:

for(int i=1;i<=5;i++)
{
    if(i==3)
    {
        continue;
    }

    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1
2
4
5

return Statement

Used to return a value from a method or stop method execution.

Example:

return;


# Advantages of Control Structures

- Controls program execution
- Reduces code complexity
- Helps in decision making
- Helps in repeating tasks
- Improves program readability
